Do you prefer the sights and sounds of the morning new or the evening end? Both hold space for anticipation and peace. 

Can you tell which this is?

#sunrise #sunset #winterlandscapes #rivertherapy #fearnofruit🍌
November photo dump. Last year we moved and life was busy. This year life is busy and mostly manageable with friends, family, dogs and fish of course in between.

I haven’t always been a winter person. I crew up in the cold Midwest where your boogers freeze with a deep breathe. I’m sure that has to do with why I left there, to avoid the winters. But in the Midwest there is still water and a fair amount of natural resources. You don’t fear the summer (other than the bugs and stinging nettle that can kill you)! I also was not a fly angler when I lived there either. I didn’t understand the west and the importance of winter. Having lived in Utah longer than Wisconsin I totally understand why I get so excited in “bad” winter weather. It’s not bad weather, it’s beneficial, and the fishing is often better. It renews.  Replenishes. It gives a place like this the ability to fuel the soul in the summer months. 🎣

Funny thing is, when it comes so snow sports, the sunnier the better for me lol! 🙃

#letitsnow #rivertherapy #happyplace #fearnofruit #lovewhereyoulive #forgettheforecast #cheesehead

One of favorite fish this year.  Daughter (15 yo) was on the sticks. We saw some super active swallows as we approached this riffle near the end of our float. I explained to G where I wanted the boat and at the top of the riffle this fish ate my dry fly as anticipated. 
She brought me over to the bank with ease to take this photo. 

Ever more than the fish I like the wrinkle in my nose this situation can bring.

Good bye 2022! I stoked this one is over. It was a roller coaster of joy and stress. We made it through. There’s no other option.

Thankful for fishing, dogs, friends, family and ROLLER SKATING that got us through. 

Cheers to a new year and more of the good stuff.

A couple things on my mind today (besides work 😏). 

I have recently became very aware that I’ve become very particular as to how I fish. It maters more to me how I catch the fish over how many fish I catch. I find so much joy swinging flies or fishing a dry with a fly I tied. That does not mean I don’t fish other ways and find joy in other aspects. I’m reflecting on my change as an angler each year that goes by. It’s fun to look back sometimes and recognize the changes that are both good or bad. 
I truly just appreciate having wet feet in a river and submerging myself in the nature even more than anything. 

Also, @utahstreamaccess was in court this morning fighting for our rights to use the water we all pay for that runs over stream beads that should be held in a public easement. Listening online this morning it sounded like it went well. Wishing USAC and all Utahans good luck! Become a member of USAC. Show support. It’s free. 

#rivertherapy #fearnofruit🍌 #keepfishwet #utahstreamaccess #lovewhereyoulive #forgettheforecast #lamsonfleet

In the words of Lori-Ann Murphy; 
“Tarpon are a hand shake from God”.

#tarpon #fearnofruit🍌 #handshakefromgod

Feeling a sense of gratitude today. 
Maybe because I woke up at 45 yo in Mexico last week and forgot it was my birthday because, Mexico! Maybe it’s because I’m on the flip side of covid for the second time 🤒. Maybe it’s because I get to watch my girls play tennis and softball this spring and be stoked they found a sport they love! Maybe it’s because I have beef stew in the crock pot on this cold winter day (ready for spring already). Maybe it’s because I always feels safe with my hubby around. Maybe it’s because all this snow gets me stoked for fishing the rest of the year! Maybe it’s because I get to fish on 🪜 next weeks with amazing women!
Maybe it’s just all the things. 💗

What are grateful for today? 

#fearnofruit🍌 #mangroves #happyplace #lovewhereyoulive

There are so many things I LOVE about this clip and this moment. We were TOTALLY in the moment for one! That’s flyfishing though right?!
We tucked into (well under) the mangroves to find a ton of tarpon rolling in the roots eating. They would come out periodically and cruise. This time the lead dog was cruising and started chasing my fly. We saw the eat, got the jump, spit the fly.
When I look back and watch this video, I see the guide try to strip set in the moment for me. I thought I was tight to the fish, but I could’ve set the hook better. In the end, it was an awesome moment to see all that activity and we both had a shot at a fish eating! 
Tarpon have had their grip on me from the first moment I met one. Can’t wait to do this again someday!
🎥 @metadesignsslc

This kind of fish is a group effort. 
Wind, snow squalls, sun, grapple, many layers, research, giggles, and some luck with @northwestflygirl and @snwadventurer made this all come together. It was OUR fish. 

Every fly strip could be the big one. I stayed focused on the prize (not my cold fingers and toes) and once I saw it turn I knew I had what we came for. So many things can go wrong. I walked it around the boat twice as it continued to nose dive like a striper would. But this was a trout (char)!!! I just couldn’t imagine finding one of these in a river system 😳 
Incredible experience and I would suffer the crazy weather (winter in spring) to do it a million more times!

Feeling defeated, I walked slowly to the car and tried a different idea and area. 

The beauty of flyfishing is there’s not end to learning, being surprised, feeling frustrated and feeling elated. 
A few fish came to hand at the 11th hour (8th really) and blew up on my fly like I’ve never heard before. So crazy.

We often don’t appreciate things we don’t work hard for.

This water year was pretty incredible on the river and somehow I found some of my biggest trout of my life. 

A lot of other “stuff” happened this years also. No one goes through life unscathed but this page is mostly about flyfishing so that’s whatcha get! If you get to know me, you’ll know more of me than just 🐟 and 🍌☺️. 
But that’s what the river does. It helps you get through all the other stuff life throws at you. 

I love to share the joy I feel on the river here and thank you for following along and sharing the stoke!

As we head into 2024 with much less than normal snow pack I really hope we start getting some weather soon. #prayforsnow❄️

I’ve heard that people go through life without a passion described as “an intense desire or enthusiasm for something”. That notion makes me sad for them. I have/have had a few passions in my life. I’ve dabble in wheel thrown pottery for most of my life as well as helping women breastfeed their babies with support and instruction through La Leche League. I love playing games!! I was an athelete in numerous sports through my life like ice skating, roller skating, gymnastics, diving, snowboarding and now fishing. I love playing pool, darts, shuffle board, and ball games. I guess one would say I’m competitive! 
Nothing has moved me more than flyfishing. This has got to go back to generations of my family (Norwegians) who have fished and made it their living. I’m grateful for all the passions I have in my life. I’m never bored! 

May you find the passion that makes your blood boil and give your peace and butterflies in your gut with excitement. What is life without these feelings from within? 
I’m glad I don’t know that void. 

I hope to one day be a CCI and teach more people to fly cast. It will happen…
